formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=0} x^(k*(k + 19)/2) / Product_{j=1..k} (1 - x^j). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 24 2020

A025156.name: A prime number of consecutive composites follow n.

A025157.name: Number of partitions of n with distinct parts p(i) such that if i != j, then |p(i) - p(j)| >= 3.

A025158.name: Number of partitions of n with distinct parts p(i) such that if i != j, then |p(i) - p(j)| >= 4.
formula: G.f.: Sum(x^(2*k^2-k)/Product(1-x^i, i=1..k), k=1..infinity). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Aug 12 2004

A025159.name: Number of partitions of n with distinct parts p(i) such that if i != j, then |p(i) - p(j)| >= 5.
formula: G.f.: Sum(x^(5/2*k^2-3/2*k)/Product(1-x^i, i=1..k), k=1..infinity). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Aug 12 2004

A025160.name: Number of partitions of n with distinct parts p(i) such that if i != j, then |p(i) - p(j)| >= 6.
formula: G.f.: Sum(x^(3*k^2-2*k)/Product(1-x^i, i=1..k), k=1..infinity). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Aug 12 2004

A025161.name: Number of partitions of n with distinct parts p(i) such that if i != j, then |p(i) - p(j)| >= 7.
formula: G.f.: Sum(x^(7/2*k^2-5/2*k)/Product(1-x^i, i=1..k), k=1..infinity). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Aug 12 2004

A025162.name: Number of partitions of n with distinct parts p(i) such that if i != j, then |p(i) - p(j)| >= 8.
formula: G.f.: Sum(x^(4*k^2-3*k)/Product(1-x^i, i=1..k), k=1..infinity). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Aug 12 2004

A025163.name: The value of the associated Legendre Polynomial of index n and order 1 evaluated at x=2^(-1/2) multiplied by 2^(3*n/2-1).

A025164.name: a(n) = a(n-2) + (2n-1)a(n-1); a(0)=1, a(1)=1.
formula: a(n) = A001147(n)*hypergeometric([-n/2+1/2, -n/2], [1/2, -n, 1/2-n], 1) for n >= 1. - _Peter Luschny_, Sep 11 2014
a(n) = -i*( BesselK(1/2, 1)*BesselI(n+1/2, -1) - BesselI(-1/2, -1)*BesselK(n+1/2, 1)) for n>=0 (a(0)=1, a(1) = 1). - _G. C. Greubel_, Apr 21 2015
a(n) = A036244(-1-n) for all n in Z.
Given e.g.f. A(x), then 0 = A(x) + 3*A'(x) + (2*x-1)*A''(x). - _Michael Somos_, Jan 10 2017
Given g.f. A(x), then 0 = 1 + (x^2+x-1)*A(x) + 2*x^2*A'(x). - _Michael Somos_, Jan 10 2017

A025165.name: a(n) = H_n(1) / 2^floor(n/2) where H_n is the n-th Hermite polynomial.

A025166.name: E.g.f.: -exp(-x/(1-2*x))/(1-2*x).
formula: Sum_{n>=0} a(n) * x^n / (n!)^2 = -exp(2*x) * BesselJ(0,2*sqrt(x)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jul 17 2020

A025167.name: E.g.f: exp(x/(1-2*x))/(1-2*x).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} k!*2^k*binomial(n, k)^2. - _Robert G. Wilson v_, Mar 16 2005 [corrected by _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Oct 01 2018]
E.g.f.: exp(2*x) * Sum_{n>=0} x^n/n!^2 = Sum_{n>=0} a(n)*x^n/n!^2. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Nov 18 2011

A025168.name: E.g.f.: exp(x/(1-2*x)).
formula: Second LAH transform of A000012. LAH transform of A000262. a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n) 2^(n-k)*n!/k!*binomial(n-1, k-1). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Oct 17 2003
Define f_1(x), f_2(x), ... such that f_1(x) = e^x, f_{n+1}(x) = (d/dx)(x^2*f_n(x)), for n=2,3,.... Then a(n) = e^(-1/2)*4*(n-1)*f_n(1/2). - _Milan Janjic_, May 30 2008
E.g.f.: E(0)/2, where E(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x/(x + (k+1)*(1-2*x)/E(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jul 09 2013

A025170.name: G.f.: 1/(1 + 2*x + 9*x^2).
formula: a(0)=1, a(1)=-2, a(n) = -(2*a(n-1)+9*a(n-2)) for n>1. - _Philippe Deléham_, Sep 19 2009

A025171.name: Reciprocal Chebyshev polynomial of second kind evaluated at 4 multiplied by (-1)^n.

A025172.name: Let phi = arccos(1/3), the dihedral angle of the regular tetrahedron. Then cos(n*phi) = a(n)/3^n.
formula: a(0) = 1, a(1) = 1; for n >= 2, a(n) = 2*a(n-1) - 9*a(n-2). - _Warut Roonguthai_, Oct 11 2005
a(n) is the permanent of the matrix M^n, where M = [i, 2; 1, i]. - _Simone Severini_, Apr 27 2007
G.f.: G(0)/2, where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(8*k+1)/(x*(8*k+9) + 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 28 2013

A025173.name: The Gegenbauer Polynomial of index n, order 1, evaluated at x=1/3 and multiplied by n*3^n/2.

A025174.name: a(n) = binomial(3n-1, n-1).
formula: G.f.: z*g^2/(1-3*z*g^2), where g=g(z) is given by g=1+z*g^3, g(0)=1, that is, (in Maple command) g := 2*sin(arcsin(3*sqrt(3*z)/2)/3)/sqrt(3*z). - _Emeric Deutsch_, May 22 2003
Hankel transform of a(n+1) is A005156(n+1). - _Paul Barry_, Apr 14 2008
G.f.: x*B'(x)/B(x) where B(x) is the g.f. of A001764. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_ Feb 03 2013
D-finite with recurrence: 2*n*(2*n-1)*a(n) -3*(3*n-1)*(3*n-2)*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Feb 05 2013
Logarithmic derivative of A001764; g.f. of A001764 satisfies G(x) = 1 + x*G(x)^3. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jul 14 2013
a(n) = [x^n] C(x)^n for n >= 1, where C(x) = (1 - sqrt(1 - 4*x))/(2*x) is the generating function for A000108 (Ramanujan). - _Peter Bala_, Jun 24 2015

Without the initial term 0, the o.g.f. equals f(x)*g(x)^2, where f(x) is the o.g.f. for A005809 and g(x) is the o.g.f. for A001764. g(x)^2 is the o.g..f for A006013. More generally, f(x)*g(x)^k is the o.g.f. for the sequence binomial(3*n + k,n). Cf. A045721 (k = 1), A004319 (k = 3), A236194 (k = 4), A013698 (k = 5), A165817 (k = -1), A117671 (k = -2). (End)

A025176.name: a(n) = Jacobi P-Polynomial P_n(alpha=1, beta=1, x=sqrt(2)) multiplied by 2^(n/2+floor(n/2)) and divided by n+1.

A025177.name: Triangular array, read by rows: first differences in n,n direction of trinomial array A027907.

A025178.name: First differences of the central trinomial coefficients A002426.
formula: a(n) = T(n,n) for n>=1, where T is the array defined in A025177.
a(n) is asymptotic to c*3^n/sqrt(n) with c around 1.02... - _Benoit Cloitre_, Nov 02 2002
D-finite with recurrence: a(n) = ((2+n)*a(n-2)+3*(3-n)*a(n-3)+3*(n-1)*a(n-1))/n, a(0)=1, a(1)=0, a(2)=2. - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 16 2012 [adapted to new offset by _Peter Luschny_, Nov 04 2015]

A025179.name: a(n) = number of (s(0), s(1), ..., s(n)) such that s(i) is an integer, s(0) = 0, |s(1)| = 1, |s(i) - s(i-1)| <= 1 for i >= 2, s(n) = 1. Also a(n) = T(n,n-1), where T is the array defined in A025177.

A025180.name: a(n) = number of (s(0), s(1), ..., s(n)) such that s(i) is an integer, s(0) = 0, |s(1)| = 1, |s(i) - s(i-1)| <= 1 for i >= 2, s(n) = 2. Also a(n) = T(n,n-2), where T is the array defined in A025177.

A025181.name: a(n) = number of (s(0), s(1), ..., s(n)) such that s(i) is an integer, s(0) = 0, |s(1)| = 1, |s(i) - s(i-1)| <= 1 for i >= 2, s(n) = 3. Also a(n) = T(n,n-3), where T is the array defined in A025177.

A025182.name: a(n) = number of (s(0), s(1), ..., s(n)) such that s(i) is an integer, s(0) = 0, |s(1)| = 1, |s(i) - s(i-1)| <= 1 for i >= 2, s(n) = 4. Also a(n) = T(n,n-4), where T is the array defined in A025177.

A025183.name: a(n) = T(2n-1,n), where T is the array defined in A025177.

A025184.name: a(n) = T(2n,n), where T is the array defined in A025177.

A025185.name: a(n) = T(3n,n), where T is the array defined in A025177.

A025186.name: T(4n,n), where T is the array defined in A025177.

A025187.name: a(n) = T(2n,n-1), where T is the array defined in A025177.

A025188.name: a(n) = T(2n,n+1), where T is the array defined in A025177.

A025189.name: a(n) = T(n,[ n/2 ]), where T is the array defined in A025177.

A025191.name: a(n) = Sum{T(n,k)}, k = 0,1,...,n, where T is the array defined in A025177.

A025192.name: a(0)=1; a(n) = 2*3^(n-1) for n >= 1.
formula: a(0) = 1, a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-1} (a(k) + a(n-k-1)). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jun 24 2003
Row sums of triangle A134318. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Oct 19 2007
a(n) = lcm(a(n-1), Sum_{k=1..n-1} a(k)) for n >= 3. - _David W. Wilson_, Sep 27 2011
For the e.g.f. E(x) = 2/3*exp(3*x) + exp(0)/3 we have
E(x) = 1+2*x/(G(0)-3*x) where G(k) = 3*x + 1 + k - 3*x*(k+1)/G(k+1); (continued fraction, Euler's 1st kind, 1-step). (End).
G.f.: 1 + (1/2/G(0) - 1)/x where G(k) = 1 - 2^k/(2 - 4*x/(2*x - 2^k/G(k+1) )); (recursively defined continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Dec 22 2012
G.f.: 1 + x*W(0), where W(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x*(2*k+3)/(x*(2*k+4) + 1/W(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 28 2013

Construct the power matrix T(n,j)=[A(n)^*j]*[S(n)^*(j-1)] where A(n)=(2,2,2,...) and S(n)=(0,1,0,0...). (* is convolution operation). Then a(n) = Sum_{j=1..n} T(n,j). - _David Neil McGrath_, Jan 01 2015

A025193.name: a(n) = [ 2nd elementary symmetric function of {sqrt(k)} ], k = 1,2,...,n.

A025194.name: a(n) = [ 3rd elementary symmetric function of {sqrt(k)} ], k = 1,2,...,n.

A025197.name: a(n) = floor( Sum_{1 <= i < j <= n} ((sqrt(j)-sqrt(i))^3) ).

A025199.name: a(n) = floor(floor(S2)/floor(S1)), where S2 and S1 are, respectively, the 2nd and first elementary symmetric functions of {sqrt(k), k = 1,2,...,n}.
formula: a(n) = floor(A025193(n) / A025224(n)). - _Sean A. Irvine_, Aug 16 2019

A025200.name: a(n) = floor(floor(S3)/floor(S1)), where S3 and S1 are, respectively, the 3rd and first elementary symmetric functions of {sqrt(k), k = 1,2,...,n}.
formula: a(n) = floor(A025194(n) / A025224(n)). - _Sean A. Irvine_, Aug 16 2019

A025201.name: a(n) = floor(log(n!)).
formula: a(n) = floor(n*log(n) - n + log(2*Pi*n)/2) (Stirling's approximation) holds for all 1 < n < 10^6, but a counterexample might exist for some larger n. - _M. F. Hasler_, Dec 03 2018

A025202.name: a(n) = [ 2nd elementary symmetric function of {log(k)} ], k = 2,3,...,n.

A025203.name: a(n) = [ 3rd elementary symmetric function of {log(k)} ], k = 2,3,...,n.

A025208.name: a(n) = [ (n-2)nd elementary symmetric function of {log(k)} ], k = 2,3,...,n.

A025209.name: a(n) = floor(floor(S2)/floor(S1)), where S2 and S1 are, respectively, the 2nd and first elementary symmetric functions of {log(k)}, k = 2,3,...,n.
formula: a(n) = floor(A025202(n) / A025201(n)). - _Sean A. Irvine_, Aug 17 2019

A025210.name: a(n) = floor(floor(S3)/floor(S1)); where S3 and S1 are, respectively, the third and first elementary symmetric functions of {log(k)}, k = 1,2,...,n.
formula: a(n) = floor(A025203(n) / A025201(n)). - _Sean A. Irvine_, Aug 18 2019

A025211.name: Expansion of 1/((1-2x)(1-3x)(1-4x)(1-5x)).
formula: If we define f(m,j,x) = Sum_{k=j..m} binomial(m,k)*stirling2(k,j)*x^(m-k) then a(n-3) = (-1)^(n-1)*f(n,3,-5), (n >= 3). - _Milan Janjic_, Apr 26 2009
If we define f(m,j,x) = Sum_{k=j..m} binomial(m,k)*stirling2(k,j)*x^(m-k) then a(n-3) = f(n,3,2), (n >= 3). - _Milan Janjic_, Apr 26 2009
E.g.f.: (d^3/dx^3) (exp(2*x)*((exp(x)-1)^3)/3!). See the Sheffer comment given above. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Oct 08 2011

A025212.name: a(n) = floor(2nd elementary symmetric function of Sum_{j=1..k} 1/j, k = 1,2,...,n).

A025213.name: a(n) = floor(3rd elementary symmetric function of Sum_{j=1..k} 1/j, k = 1,2,...,n).

A025214.name: a(n) = floor(4th elementary symmetric function of Sum_{j=1..k} 1/j, k = 1,2,...,n).

A025215.name: a(n) = [ Sum of squares of 1 + 1/2 + ... + 1/k ], k = 1,2,...,n.

A025219.name: a(n) = [ 2nd elementary symmetric function of {sqrt(k+1)} ], k = 1,2,...,n.

A025221.name: [ 4th elementary symmetric function of sqrt(k+1) ], k = 1,2,...,n.

A025224.name: a(n) = floor(Sum_{k=1..n} sqrt(k)).
formula: a(n) ~= floor ((4n + 3)sqrt(n)/6 - exp(-Pi / 2)). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jul 29 2007. Corrected by _Carl R. White_, Jan 22 2009

A025225.name: a(n) = a(1)*a(n-1) + a(2)*a(n-2) + ...+ a(n-1)*a(1) for n >= 2. Also a(n) = (2^n)*C(n-1), where C = A000108 (Catalan numbers).
formula: Given g.f. C(x) and given A(x)= g.f. of A100238, then B(x)=A(x)-1-x satisfies B(x)=x-C(x*B(x)). - _Michael Somos_, Sep 07 2005

A025226.name: a(n) = a(1)*a(n-1) + a(2)*a(n-2) + ...+ a(n-1)*a(1) for n >= 2. Also a(n) = 3^n*C(n-1), where C = A000108 (Catalan numbers).
formula: Given g.f. C(x) and given A(x)= g.f. of A100239, then B(x)=A(x)-1-2x satisfies B(x)=x-C(x*B(x)). - _Michael Somos_, Sep 07 2005
G.f.: (1 - U(0))/x where U(k)= 1 - 3*x/U(k+1) ; (continued fraction, 1-step). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Oct 30 2012
D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) +6*(3-2*n)*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Nov 12 2012

A025227.name: a(n) = a(1)*a(n-1) + a(2)*a(n-2) + ... + a(n-1)*a(1) for n >= 3.
formula: a(n) = sum(C(n-k-1)*binomial(n-k, k), k=0..floor(n/2)), where C(q)=binomial(2q, q)/(q+1) are the Catalan numbers (A000108). - _Emeric Deutsch_, Nov 14 2001
D-finite with recurrence n*a(n) = (4n-6)*a(n-1)+(4n-12)*a(n-2), n>2. a(1)=1, a(2)=2.
G.f. satisfies A(x)-A(x)^2 = x+x^2. - _Ralf Stephan_, Jun 30 2003
a(n) = sum{k=0..n-1, C(k)C(k+1, n-k-1)} - _Paul Barry_, Feb 23 2005
G.f. A(x) satisfies A(x)=x+C(2x*A(x)) where C(x) is g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108 offset 1. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 08 2005

Given an integer t >= 1 and initial values u = [a_0, a_1, ..., a_{t-1}], we may define an infinite sequence Phi(u) by setting a_n = a_{n-1} + a_0*a_{n-1} + a_1*a_{n-2} + ... + a_{n-2}*a_1 for n >= t. For example Phi([1]) is the Catalan numbers A000108. The present sequence is (essentially) Phi([1,2]). - _Gary W. Adamson_, Oct 27 2008
a(n+1), n >= 0, is column sum for the n-th column of the table R(m,n)=binomial(m+1, n-m)c(m) where c(m) is the m-th Catalan number A000108.
The table entry is nonzero if and only if m <= n <= 2m+1.

R(m,n) gives the number of Rota-Baxter words in one idempotent generator x and one operator of degree m and arity n, or the number of ways of adding m pairs of parentheses to a string of n x's (n necessarily lies between m and 2m+1 inclusive for a nonzero count), such that no two pairs of parentheses are immediately nested and no two x's remain adjacent. (End)
G.f.: A(x) = B(B(x)) where B(x) is the g.f. of A182399. -_Paul D. Hanna_, Apr 27 2012
G.f.: 1 - x + x*G(0), where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - (1+x)/(1 + x/G(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 01 2013
O.g.f.: A(x) = x*S(x/(1 + x)), where S(x) = (1 - x - sqrt(1 - 6*x + x^2))/(2*x) is the o.g.f. for the large Schröder numbers A006318. - _Peter Bala_, Mar 05 2020
G.f.: A(x) satisfies ((A(x) - A(-x))/(2*x))^2 = S(4*x^2), where S(x) is the g.f. for the large Schröder numbers A006318. - _Alexander Burstein_, May 20 2021

A025229.name: a(n) = a(1)*a(n-1) + a(2)*a(n-2) + ...+ a(n-1)*a(1) for n >= 3.
formula: Another recurrence formula: n*a(n) = (4*n-6)*a(n-1)+(8*n-24)*a(n-2). - _Richard Choulet_, Dec 16 2009

A025230.name: a(n) = a(1)*a(n-1) + a(2)*a(n-2) + ...+ a(n-1)*a(1) for n >= 3.
formula: D-finite with recurrence n*a(n) = (12*n-18)*a(n-1) - 32*(n-3)*a(n-2) - _Richard Choulet_, Dec 17 2009
a(n+1) = GegenbauerC(n-1, -n, -3)/n for n>=1. - _Peter Luschny_, May 09 2016

A025231.name: a(n) = a(1)*a(n-1) + a(2)*a(n-2) + ...+ a(n-1)*a(1) for n >= 3.
formula: Another recurrence formula: n*a(n) = (8*n - 12)*a(n - 1) - (4*n - 12)*a(n - 2) [From _Richard Choulet_, Dec 16 2009]
G.f.: 1 + x - G(0); G(k) = 1 + 2*x - 3*x/G(k + 1); (continued fraction, 1-step). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jan 05 2012
G.f.: x + x/W(0), where W(k)= 1 - 2*x - x/W(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 16 2013 [Edited by _Michael Somos_, Apr 10 2014]

A025234.name: An L-tile is a 2 X 2 square with the upper 1 X 1 subsquare removed; no rotations are allowed. a(n) = number of tilings of a 4 X n rectangle using tiles that are either 1 X 1 squares or L-tiles.

A025235.name: a(n) = (1/2)*s(n+2), where s = A014431.
formula: G.f. (for offset 1) is series reversion of x / (1 + x + 2*x^2). - _Michael Somos_, Jul 12 2003.
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n, k)*2^(k/2)*C(k/2)*(1+(-1)^k)/2, where C(n)=A000108(n). - _Paul Barry_, Dec 22 2003
a(n) is the leftmost term in the top row of M^n, M is an infinite square production matrix as follows:
G.f.: 1/(1 - x - 2*x^2/(1 - x - 2*x^2/(1 - x - 2*x^2/(1 - x - 2*x^2/(1 - ....))))), a continued fraction. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 26 2017

A025237.name: Expansion of (1 -x -sqrt(1-2*x-11*x^2))/(6*x^2).
formula: D-finite with recurrence: (n+2)*a(n) - (2*n+1)*a(n-1) + 11*(1-n)*a(n-2) = 0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Nov 15 2011
G.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = 1 + x * (1 + 3*x*A(x)^2) / (1 - x). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jun 30 2020

A025242.name: Generalized Catalan numbers.
formula: G.f.: 2 + x - x*G(0), where G(k)= 1 - 1/(1 - x/(1 - x/(1 - x/(1 - x/(x - 1/G(k+1) ))))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jul 12 2013

A025250.name: a(n) = a(1)*a(n-1) + a(2)*a(n-2) + ...+ a(n-3)*a(3) for n >= 4.
formula: G.f.: x^2+x^3*(1/(1-x^2))c(x^3/(1-x^2)^2) where c(x) is the g.f. of A000108. - _Paul Barry_, May 20 2009
G.f.: K_{k>=0} (-x^3)/(x^2-1), where K is the Gauss notation for a continued fraction. - _Benedict W. J. Irwin_, Oct 11 2016

A025252.name: (1/2)*s(n+3), where s = A025251.
formula: a(n) = A160565(n) for all n>0. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 08 2015

A025262.name: a(n) = a(1)*a(n-1) + a(2)*a(n-2) + ...+ a(n-1)*a(1) for n >= 4.
formula: G.f.: (1 - sqrt(1 - 4*x + 4*x^3)) / 2. Satisfies A(x) - A(x)^2 = x - x^3. - _Michael Somos_, Aug 04, 2000

Comment from _Gary W. Adamson_, Oct 27 2008: Given an integer t >= 1 and initial values u = [a_0, a_1, ..., a_{t-1}], we may define an infinite sequence Phi(u) by setting a_n = a_{n-1} + a_0*a_{n-1} + a_1*a_{n-2} + ... + a_{n-2}*a_1 for n >= t. For example Phi([1]) is the Catalan numbers A000108. The present sequence is Phi([1,1,1]).
Row sums of A176703 if offset 0. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 09 2012
a(n)=sum(m=0..floor((n-1)/2), C(n-2*m-1)*binomial(n-2*m,m)*(-1)^m), where C = A000108 are the Catalan numbers. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Jan 26 2013

A025265.name: a(n) = a(1)*a(n-1) + a(2)*a(n-2) + ... + a(n-1)*a(1) for n >= 4.
formula: G.f. A(x) satisfies 0=f(x, A(x)) where f(x, y)=(x-x^2+x^3)-(y-y^2). - _Michael Somos_, May 26 2005
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} C(k)*Sum_{j=0..k+1} binomial(j,n-k-j-1)*binomial(k+1,j)*(-1)^(-n+k-1), where C(k) is Catalan numbers (A000108)  - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, May 10 2018

Partial sums of A069513. - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, May 30 2011
a(n) = Sum_{m=1..n} A001222(m) * A002321(floor(n/m)) where A001222() is the Omega function and A002321() is the Mertens function.

a(n) = Sum_{m=1..floor(log_2(n))} A000010(m)/m * J(floor(n^(1/m))) where A000010() is Euler's totient function and J(n) = Sum_{m=1..floor(log_2(n))} 1/m * A000720(floor(n^(1/m))) is Riemann's prime-power counting function.

A025531.name: a(n) = (2nd elementary symmetric function of {1/1, 1/2, ..., 1/n})*(lcm(S))^2, where S = {1,2,...,n}.

A025538.name: a(n) = (1/s(1) - 1/s(2) + ... + d/s(n+1)) * LCM{1, 2, ..., n}, where d = (-1)^n, s = A002944, i.e., s(k) = LCM of row k of Pascal's triangle.

If n = 2^k - 1, then a(n) = A099996(n) = A003418(2*n); otherwise a(n) = A099996(n)/2 = A003418(2*n)/2. - _Max Alekseyev_, Apr 13 2016

A025748.name: 3rd order Patalan numbers (generalization of Catalan numbers).
formula: D-finite with recurrence n*a(n) +3*(4-3*n)*a(n-1) = 0, n>=2. - _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 29 2012
For n>0, a(n) = 9^(n-1) * Gamma(n-1/3) / (n * Gamma(2/3) * Gamma(n)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Feb 09 2014

A025749.name: 4th order Patalan numbers (generalization of Catalan numbers).

A025755.name: 10th-order Patalan numbers (generalization of Catalan numbers).
formula: a(n) = 100^(n-1)*Pochhammer(9/10, n-1)/n! for n >= 1.  Maple confirms this satisfies Mathar's conjecture for n >= 2 (it's not true for n=1). - _Robert Israel_, Oct 05 2014

A025756.name: 3rd order Vatalan numbers (generalization of Catalan numbers).
formula: a(n) = sum(m=1..n-1, m/n * sum(k=1..n-m, binomial(k,n-m-k) * 3^k*(-1)^(n-m-k) * binomial(n+k-1,n-1)))+1. [_Vladimir Kruchinin_, Feb 08 2011]

A025757.name: 4th order Vatalan numbers (generalization of Catalan numbers).
formula: a(n) = sum(m=1..n-1, m/n*4^(n-m) * sum(k=1..n-m, binomial(n+k-1,n-1) * sum(j=0..k, binomial(j,n-m-3*k+2*j) * 4^(j-k) * binomial(k,j) * 3^(-n+m+3*k-j) * 2^(n-m-3*k+j) * (-1)^(n-m-3*k+2*j))))+1. [From _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Feb 08 2011]

A025758.name: 5th-order Vatalan numbers (generalization of Catalan numbers).
formula: a(n) = sum(m=1..n-1, 5^(n-m)*m/n * sum(k=1..n-m, binomial(n+k-1,n-1) * sum(i=0..k, binomial(k,i) * 2^(k-i) * sum(j=0..i, binomial(j,-3*i+n-m-k+2*j) * (-1)^(j-i)*5^(j-i)*(-2)^(3*i-n+m+k-j) * binomial(i,j)))))+1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Feb 09 2011

A025767.name: Expansion of 1/((1-x)*(1-x^3)*(1-x^4)).
formula: Euler transform of length 4 sequence [1, 0, 1, 1]. - _Michael Somos_, Nov 09 2007
a(n) = a(-8 - n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Nov 09 2007
a(n) = Sum_{k=1..floor((n+4)/4)} Sum_{j=k..floor((n+4-k)/3)} Sum_{i=j..floor((n+4-j-k)/2)} [j = i], where [ ] is the Iverson bracket. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jan 17 2021

A025769.name: Expansion of 1/((1-x)(1-x^3)(1-x^8)).
formula: a(n) = floor((x^2+12x+c)/48) with 51 <= c <= 58. - _M. F. Hasler_, Sep 16 2012

A025795.name: Expansion of 1/((1-x^2)*(1-x^3)*(1-x^5)).
formula: If ||A|| is the nearest number to A (A not a half-integer) we also have a(n) = ||((n+1)*(n+9)/60) + (1/5)[0; 1; 1; 0; 3]. - _Richard Choulet_, Jan 20 2008
Euler transform of length 5 sequence [0, 1, 1, 0, 1]. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 05 2008
a(n) = a(-10-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 25 2008

A025799.name: Expansion of 1/((1-x^2)(1-x^3)(1-x^10)).
formula: a(n) = a(-15 - n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Nov 16 2005

A025810.name: Expansion of 1/((1-x^2)(1-x^5)(1-x^10)) in powers of x.
formula: Euler transform of length 10 sequence [ 0, 1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1]. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 18 2012
a(n) = a(-17 - n) = a(n - 10) + A008616(n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 18 2012

A025876.name: Expansion of 1/((1-x^5)(1-x^6)(1-x^7)).
formula: For n > 0, a(n) = Sum_{k=1..floor(n/4)} Sum_{j=k..floor((n-k)/3)} Sum_{i=j..floor((n-j-k)/2)} [3*k = n-i-j], where [ ] is the Iverson bracket. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jan 06 2021

A025966.name: Expansion of 1/((1-2x)(1-4x)(1-6x)(1-8x)).
formula: a(n) = (2^n)*stirling2(n+4, 4), n>=0, with stirling2(n, m)=A008277(n, m).
